<div id="review_1135189185" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1135189185" />
    <a title="CrabbyPatty" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/38069174-crabbypatty"><img alt="CrabbyPatty" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1431833720p2/38069174.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1135189185?book_show_action=true">Dec 18, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="CrabbyPatty" class="user" itemprop="url" name="CrabbyPatty" href="/user/show/38069174-crabbypatty">CrabbyPatty</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38069174-crabbypatty?shelf=true-crime">true-crime</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38069174-crabbypatty?shelf=2019-reads">2019-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38069174-crabbypatty?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1135189185" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9399979871835237995">I re-read this book every few years. Quite a few years ago, I worked for a magazine publisher focusing on law enforcement organizations, i.e. police chiefs, sheriffs, troopers, etc. One of the Oregon troopers was familiar with this case and the various law enforcement people involved, and mentioned that Ann Rule was writing a book about it. Couldn&apos;t <i>wait</i> to read the book back then, and I still feel the same sense of heartbreak each time I read it.<br/><br/><b>2019</b>: Reread this book and am still awed by Rule&apos;</span>
  <span id="freeText9399979871835237995" style="display:none">I re-read this book every few years. Quite a few years ago, I worked for a magazine publisher focusing on law enforcement organizations, i.e. police chiefs, sheriffs, troopers, etc. One of the Oregon troopers was familiar with this case and the various law enforcement people involved, and mentioned that Ann Rule was writing a book about it. Couldn't <i>wait</i> to read the book back then, and I still feel the same sense of heartbreak each time I read it.<br /><br /><b>2019</b>: Reread this book and am still awed by Rule's skill in putting together this almost unbelievable story of murder. Diane Downs' own words are enough to convict her, but Rule provides a solid background and framework of all the work done to bring her to trial. Still one of the best true crime books I've read.<br /><br /><a href="https://truecrimebook.blogspot.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">Visit my new blog "I Love True Crime Books"</a><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9399979871835237995" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


