<div id="review_3978995883" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3978995883" />
    <a title="Taylor Walworth" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4815836-taylor-walworth"><img alt="Taylor Walworth" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1619984434p2/4815836.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3978995883?book_show_action=true">Nov 30, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Taylor Walworth" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Taylor Walworth" href="/user/show/4815836-taylor-walworth">Taylor Walworth</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780593335178" href="/book/show/55573802-small-sacrifices">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3978995883" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12566267152028311276">A properly fascinating crime, conveyed via a truly exhaustive degree of detail. I&apos;m now convinced that I can&apos;t ever get fully behind true crime authors who include whole interview/interrogation transcripts in their books, even when it is Ann Rule; SMALL SACRIFICES makes me grateful that I read her seminal true crime book, THE STRANGER BESIDE ME, first, because I don&apos;t think I could have carried on with her after this one, and that book is basically my life support mechanism (#basicbitch). She&apos;s </span>
  <span id="freeText12566267152028311276" style="display:none">A properly fascinating crime, conveyed via a truly exhaustive degree of detail. I'm now convinced that I can't ever get fully behind true crime authors who include whole interview/interrogation transcripts in their books, even when it is Ann Rule; SMALL SACRIFICES makes me grateful that I read her seminal true crime book, THE STRANGER BESIDE ME, first, because I don't think I could have carried on with her after this one, and that book is basically my life support mechanism (#basicbitch). She's a meticulous researcher, obviously, but she has some persistent... shall we say, writing quirks, that grate on the nerves over the course of 500 pages.<br /><br />That said, this book did have the effect of making me curious about what a modern treatment of Diane Downs might look like. Let me be clear, she's a harrowing figure, her crimes were monstrous (as is her continued lack of remorse), and she is exactly where she deserves to be.... but SMALL SACRIFICES and Rule's treatment of her seemed very much 'of its time' (I mean, a writer ranking their subject's sexual partners according to frequency of orgasm will always make me super un-comfy, regardless of the time period and even when that subject is a woman who shot her own kids), and I suppose I just wonder how we might write of her now. Not necessarily with compassion, but with a greater, more evolved understanding of the numerous factors that made her what she ended up being.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12566267152028311276" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

